    <stitle>VT 365 Diesel Engine - 2004 Model Year - CYLINDER HEAD AND VALVE TRAIN - Installation - Cylinder Head
        Assembly
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc id="s26504.4.3" graphiccount="2">
        <title>Cylinder Head Assembly</title>
        <svcsubproc id="s26504.4.3.2">
            <title>Install Valves</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Clean valve faces and seats with a suitable cleaning solvent to remove all dirt or
                    foreign material.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To prevent personal injury or death, wear safety glasses with side shields to protect eyes.
                        Limit compressed air pressure to 207 kPa (30 psi).
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Blow dry all new and used components.</para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Guides must be clean.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Clean guides with valve guide brush.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Dry valve guides with filtered compressed air.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Lubricate the inside diameter of the new valve stem seal with clean engine oil and
                    install valve seal over valve guide until it stops.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Valve seal will not seat completely over valve guide by hand. Seals can be seated using a deep
                        socket and a rubber mallet to provide a positive contact with the machined base.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f2650476" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figD08/D08193.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="312px" box="no"/>
                <caption>Installation of valve seal, spring, and retainer</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Valve seal</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Valve spring</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Valve retainer</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Place valve spring over valve stem seal.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install a valve spring retainer on top of spring.</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f2650477" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figD08/D08174.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Installation of valve retainer key</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Valve retainer key</callout1>
                    <callout1 type="arabic">Valve spring compression tool</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Attach "C" Type Valve Spring Compressor and compress the valve spring. Install the
                    retainer keys and release valve spring compression tool.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <caution>
                    <para>To prevent engine damage, make sure retainer keys are correctly seated in each valve stem.
                    </para>
                </caution>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">After valve replacement, measure valve head recession relative to deck to confirm
                    reconditioning. See Specifications .
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
